# **SPACE MARINE SPECIAL RULES**

### **And They Shall Know No Fear**

Automatically passes regroup tests at the start of the turn and may be used normally for the rest of the turn. If caught by a pursuit, they automatically regroup and are re-engaged in close combat, and do not suffer extra wounds from being caught in a pursuit.  Immune to ***Fear***.

### **Chapter Tactics**

Each Space Marine Chapter has a unique culture that influences their doctrines and tactics.  A Space Marines model with the Special Rule Chapter Tactics has all the rules conferred by the Detachment’s Chapter Selection listed under the  Special Rules section.  Any model without the Chapter Tactics Special Rule does not benefit from the Detachment’s Chapter Tactics.

When constructing your army list, you must choose one of the Chapters from the [Chapters of the Astartes](#chapters-of-the-astartes) section. Each detachment in your army may only include Space Marines from a single Chapter. For the purposes of restrictions when selecting additional detachments, all Space Marine Chapters are considered to belong to the same faction.

### **Combat Squads**

It is sound doctrine for Space Marine units to remain flexible, splitting into two entities as the tactical situation dictates.  
A full strength, ten-man unit with this special rule can break down into two five-man units, called combat squads, considered to be two five-man squads of the same type. For example, a ten-man Tactical Squad can split into two five-man Tactical Squads using the Combat Squads special rule.

You must decide which units are splitting into combat squads, and which models go into each combat squad, immediately before determining your Warlord Traits. A unit split into combat squads therefore is now two separate units for all game purposes, including calculating the total number of units in the army and determining the number of units you can place in Reserve. Then proceed with deployment as normal. In an exception to the normal rules, two combat squads split from the same unit can embark in the same transport vehicle, providing its Transport Capacity allows. Once you have decided whether or not to split a unit into combat squads, it must remain that way for the entire battle. It cannot split up or join back together later on in the battle, nor can you use a redeployment to split up a unit or join it back together.

Note that Bike Squads count as being at full strength when they have eight Space Marine Bikers and one Attack Bike. If split into combat squads, one combat squad will have five Bikers, the other will have three Bikers and the Attack Bike.

### **Command Retinue**

Among the ranks of the Adeptus Astartes, the Space Marine commanders are often accompanied by a retinue of their most trusted and elite battle-brothers. These warriors form a Command Squad, handpicked by the Chapter’s finest to support their leader in the most crucial of battles. This squad not only serves as the eyes and ears of their commander but also as his sword and shield, ready to lay down their lives in the name of the Emperor and the Chapter. Together, they form a cohesive unit, blending their martial prowess with their commander’s strategic genius to strike with precision and overwhelming force.

A model with the Command Retinue special rule may be accompanied by a Honour Guard Squad. The Honor Guard Squad must be paid for separately and may take any upgrades available to a normal Honor Guard Squad as detailed in its Unit Profile. The model with the Command Retinue special rule and the Honour Guard Squad count as a single HQ choice and unit (and must maintain squad cohesion at all time).  If an Honour Guard Squad is taken using this rule, the model with this special rule loses the Independent Character special rule, if it had it.

### **Relic of the Past**

Vehicles bearing the Relic of the Past special rule are remnants of the ancient and revered Heresy Era, their designs and capabilities far beyond the standard war machines of the current era. These relics are treasures of immense value, preserved and maintained by the most skilled Techmarines. Due to their rarity and the reverence in which they are held, only a limited number of these vehicles can be deployed in battle.

At the beginning of the game, roll a D6 for each vehicle with the Relic of the Past special rule. The vehicle gains a special enhancement based on the result, reflecting its ancient and venerable nature.

| Roll | Result | Effect |
| ----- | :---- | :---- |
| 1 | Blessing of the Omnissiah | The vehicle's Machine Spirit has been awakened. It gains ***It Will Not Die*** for the duration of the battle. |
| 2 | Reinforced Adamantium Hull | The vehicle’s ancient armor plating is near impervious. Increase either its Front or Side Armor values by 1 (not exceeding 14).  This does not change the number of Structure Points it has. |
| 3 | Augury Scanner Array | The vehicle is equipped with a sophisticated sensor array. The vehicle and any unit within 6" gain the ***Night Vision*** and ***Interceptor*** special rules. |
| 4 | Enhanced Reactor Output | The vehicle's power core is operating at peak efficiency. It gains \+1" Movement and may re-roll failed Dangerous Terrain tests. |
| 5 | Relic Weaponry | The vehicle's weapons are finely tuned relics of war. One weapon of your choice gains \+1 Strength for the duration of the battle. |
| 6 | Martial Legacy | The vehicle inspires nearby troops with its mere presence. Friendly units within 6" gain \+1 Leadership while the vehicle is operational. |

An army may include only one vehicle with the Relic of the Past special rule for every full 1000 points in the army list’s point limit. For example, in a 2000-point army, up to two vehicles with the Relic of the Past special rule may be included. If the point limit is 1500, only one such vehicle may be fielded, as there is only one full multiple of 1000 in the point limit.

